      <dsc><c level="series">
            <did><unittitle>Series I: Correspondence, <unitdate type="inclusive">1951-1967,
                     </unitdate>
                        <unitdate>Undated</unitdate>
                    </unittitle>
            </did>
            <scopecontent><p>Series I primarily contains correspondence between Gold and his editor, Seymour
                  Lawrence, between 1951 and 1960. It was during this time that Lawrence worked for
                  Gold's publisher, Little, Brown, and Co. Although some of the correspondence is
                  personal, the majority relates specifically to the writing, publication, and
                  review of his written works. Among letters from Seymour Lawrence are letters from
                  Nancy Reynolds, Gold's copy editor, Saul Bellow, Robert Brustein, Herbert Gold,
                  Merle Miller, Mark Schorer, and Mark Van Doren. In addition to these letters,
                  folder 1 contains correspondence concerning litigation (1965) in regard to Harry
                  Bridges, the International Longshore and Warehouse Union (ILWU), and the Longshore
                  Jobs Defense Committee, the latter of which Gold was a member. </p>
            </scopecontent>
